04962nam a22007335i 9781477326022DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20222022txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814773260227 a10.7560/3260152doi  a(DE-B1597)642464  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPN1995 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a809.933529682231 aUlibarri, Kristy L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aVisible Borders, Invisible Economies :bLiving Death in Latinx Narratives /cKristy L. Ulibarri. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (282 p.) :b18 b&w photos; one 8-page color insert  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLatinx: The Future Is Now00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Imagination in the Age of National Security and Market Neoliberalization -- tPART I. Documenting the Living Dead -- t1 Games of Enterprise and Security in Luis Alberto Urrea, Valeria Luiselli, and Karla Cornejo Villavicencio -- t2 Documenting the US-Mexico Border: Photography, Movement, and Paradox -- t3 Latinx Realisms: The Cinematic Borderworlds of Josefina López, David Riker, and Alex Rivera -- tPART II. Imagining the Living Dead -- t4 Markets of Resurrection: Cat Ghosts, Aztec Zombies, and the Living Dead Economy -- t5 Speculative Governances of the Dead: The Underclass, Underworld, and Undercommons -- tCoda: Dreaming of Deportation, or, When Everything “Goes South” -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGlobalization in the United States can seem paradoxical: free trade coincides with fortification of the southern border, while immigration is reimagined as a national-security threat. US politics turn aggressively against Latinx migrants and subjects even as post-NAFTA markets become thoroughly reliant on migrant and racialized workers. But in fact, there is no incongruity here. Rather, anti-immigrant politics reflect a strategy whereby capital uses specialized forms of violence to create a reserve army of the living, laboring dead. Visible Borders, Invisible Economies turns to Latinx literature, photography, and films that render this unseen scheme shockingly vivid. Works such as Valeria Luiselli’s Tell Me How It Ends and Alex Rivera’s Sleep Dealer crystallize the experience of Latinx subjects and migrants subjugated to social death, their political existence erased by disenfranchisement and racist violence while their bodies still toil in behalf of corporate profits. In Kristy L. Ulibarri’s telling, art clarifies what power obscures: the national-security state performs anti-immigrant and xenophobic politics that substitute cathartic nationalism for protections from the free market while ensuring maximal corporate profits through the manufacture of disposable migrant labor.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aGovernment, Resistance tozUnited States. 0aLatin Americans in literature. 0aLatin Americans in motion pictures. 0aLatin AmericansxViolence againstzUnited States. 0aLatin AmericanszUnited StatesxEconomic conditions. 0aLatin AmericanszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aNational securityxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aNeoliberalism and literaturezUnited States. 0aNeoliberalism in literature. 0aNeoliberalismxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076651640uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32601540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477326022423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477326022/original  a978-3-11-076651-6  Univers